When you set `window.location.href` to an empty string (`""`), it will redirect the user to the current URL, effectively reloading the page. This is because the empty string acts as a relative URL to the current page, and assigning it to `window.location.href` is equivalent to navigating to the same URL.

However, if you pass an equals sign (`=`) in the URL string, it could break the URL because it is a special character in the URL syntax and has a special meaning. In most cases, it is used to separate query parameters from the base URL or from each other.

For example:

```
// This URL sets the "id" parameter to "123" and the "type" parameter to "book"
// separated by the equals sign
window.location.href = "https://example.com/book?id=123&type=book";
```

If you pass just an equals sign as a parameter value or use it in an invalid way, it may cause unexpected behavior or errors. Therefore, it's important to properly encode and escape any special characters in a URL before assigning it to `window.location.href`.

